However, despite this significant milestone, OPTN allocation policy may benefit from further refinements such as adoption of treatment response assessment criteria after locoregional therapy (LRT) and categorization criteria for lesions with atypical imaging appearances that are not specific for HCC. In this review, we detail the changes to OPTN HCC classification to achieve alignment with LI-RADS, discuss current limitations of the OPTN classification, and explore future directions.
